<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: LA HABRA; DRYING CLOTHES IN THE FRONT YARD WON'T WASH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Even though the City Council has adopted an ordinance allowing residents to 
use clotheslines, it banned any clothes drying on front yards. 
</P>
<P>
 The move, which Councilman William D. Mahoney said will keep La Habra from 
"oppressing poor people," is being seen the opposite way by residents who heard 
of the new law this week. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are already poor. A lot of people will continue drying their clothes in 
their front yards because they have no place else to dry their clean clothes," 
said Juan Maciel, a longtime Grace Avenue resident. "The city is making life 
even tougher for poor people. Not only can we not afford to buy dryers, but now 
we won't be able to pay the fines if we get cited for drying our clothes." 
</P>
<P>
 City Manager Lee Risner said it is unlikely the city will fine residents for 
violating the new law and that if people are caught drying laundry on front 
yards, the city "will do whatever it can to help the residents solve the 
problem." 
</P>
<P>
 Council members had postponed voting on the ordinance five times since July, 
when outraged residents accused them of trying to discriminate against the 
poor. The original ordinance proposed banning clotheslines in front and side 
yards visible from the street. 
</P>
<P>
 The law prohibits people from drying clothes on front yards altogether. But 
most residents will be allowed to dry clothes on side yards, city officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 "A lot has been made of the clothesline situation," Mahoney said at last 
week's council meeting. "We're just going to have to learn that you can't make 
everybody buy dryers. . . . I don't want to go out and tell poor people, 'You 
can't dry clothes.' Let's just say what we're trying to say." 
</P>
<P>
 While some residents dislike the ordinance and predict that it will cause 
financial hardships, others are happy it will allow them to continue drying 
their clothes on their side yards. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm glad I'll still be able to dry my clothes on the fence beside my home," 
said Carmen Reyes, who had opposed the original ordinance. "At least I'll be 
able to do that."MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
