<BYLINE>
<P>
By HOLLY J. WAGNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Fire Department has received a $5,304 grant from the state Department of 
Toxic Substances Control. 
</P>
<P>
 The grant was about $3,000 less than the department had requested, but is 
still enough to pay for a laptop computer for the city's hazardous-materials 
response crew van. 
</P>
<P>
 Fire Department spokesman Paul Mathias said the computer will allow 
firefighters easy access to volumes of information in cumbersome books and 
should shorten containment time for many incidents. 
</P>
<P>
 The Newport Beach crew works in conjunction with one from Huntington Beach to 
respond to hazardous-materials emergencies in northwestern Orange County 
cities. HOLLY J. WAGNER 
