<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101194-0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 087615 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
October 11, 1994, Tuesday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 6; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
112 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: TRAVEL AND TOURISM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Chris Woodyard, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sprucing Up II: The Hyatt Regency Irvine, also near the airport, is completing 
its own $4-million renovation. 
</P>
<P>
 The 536-room hotel is redoing its lobby, corridors, two restaurants and 
meeting rooms. 
</P>
<P>
 A color scheme of taupe, coral, blue and cream will greet visitors in the 
lobby. The Ciao Mein restaurant, where Italian and Chinese cuisines blend, will 
receive a mocha-and-black treatment while the casual poolside Le Cafe will be 
done in green carpeting, white walls and rattan furniture. 
</P>
<P>
 "The renovation is part of our ongoing program to continually update the 
property to provide quality meeting and guest accommodations," said Rod 
Schinnerer, general manager. 
</P>
